  "prompt": "How do you determine the pH of hydrofluoric acid?",
  "response": "To determine the pH of a hydrofluoric acid (HF) solution, you can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Understand the Chemical Properties**: Hydrofluoric acid is a weak acid that partially ionizes in water. Its dissociation can be represented by the equation:\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{HF} \\rightleftharpoons \\text{H}^+ + \\text{F}^-\n   \\]\n\n2. **Identify the Acid Dissociation Constant (Ka)**: The strength of HF as a weak acid can be expressed with its acid dissociation constant (Ka). For HF, the \\(K_a\\) is approximately \\(6.6 \\times 10^{-4}\\) at 25 \u00b0C. \n\n3. **Set Up the Expression**: For the dissociation of HF, the Ka expression is given by:\n\n   \\[\n   K_a = \\frac{[\\text{H}^+][\\text{F}^-]}{[\\text{HF}]}\n   \\]\n\n   If we start with a concentration of HF, let's denote it as \\(C\\) (in mol/L).\n\n4. **Construct the Equilibrium Expression**: If \\(x\\) is the amount that dissociates, then at equilibrium:\n\n   - \\([\\text{H}^+] = x\\)\n   - \\([\\text{F}^-] = x\\)\n   - \\([\\text{HF}] = C - x\\)\n\n   Therefore, you can substitute into the Ka expression:\n\n   \\[\n   K_a = \\frac{x^2}{C - x}\n   \\]\n\n5. **Assume \\(x\\) is Small (if applicable)**: For weak acids, if \\(C\\) is much larger than \\(K_a\\), you can often simplify by assuming \\(C - x \\approx C\\). Thus:\n\n   \\[\n   K_a \\approx \\frac{x^2}{C}\n   \\]\n\n   Solving for \\(x\\):\n\n   \\[\n   x = \\sqrt{K_a \\cdot C}\n   \\]\n\n6. **Calculate [H\u207a] and pH**: The concentration of \\(H^+\\) ions (\\(x\\)) gives you the acidity of the solution. Finally, to find the pH, you can use the formula:\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{pH} = -\\log[\\text{H}^+]\n   \\]\n   \n   Substitute \\(x\\) into this equation to get the pH.\n\n### Example Calculation\nIf you have a 0.1 M solution of HF:\n\n1. Calculate \\(x\\):\n\n   \\[\n   K_a = 6.6 \\times 10^{-4}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   x = \\sqrt{(6.6 \\times 10^{-4})(0.1)} \\approx \\sqrt{6.6 \\times 10^{-5}} \\approx 8.12 \\times 10^{-3} \\, \\text{M}\n   \\]\n\n2. Calculate pH:\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{pH} = -\\log(8.12 \\times 10^{-3}) \\approx 2.09\n   \\]\n\nSo, the pH of a 0.1 M solution of HF would be approximately 2.09.\n\n### Note\nFor precise calculations, especially for very dilute solutions of weak acids where the approximation might not hold, it's better to solve the quadratic equation that arises from the Ka expression.",
